ar Charts \u2013 Top 100 Singles 2007|publisher=[[Australian Recording Industry Association]]|accessdate=2011-01-08}}</ref>\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|94\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{will.i.am}}\n\n[[Category:2007 singles]]\n[[Category:Will.i.am songs]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by will.i.am]]\n[[Category:Songs written by will.i.am]]\n[[Category:2007 songs]]\n[[Category:A&M Records singles]]\n[[Category:Sampling controversies]]\n", "name_user": "Hoof Hearted", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eWeekly charts:converted German chart identifier from \"Germany\" (obsolete) to \"Germany2\" and added songid.  SeeTemplate:singlechart", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/I_Got_It_from_My_Mama"}
{"title_page": "1907 Tour de France", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2019}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Infobox cycling race report\n| name               = 1907 Tour de France\n| image              = Tour de France 1907 map-fr.svg\n| image_caption      = Route of the 1907 Tour de France followed clockwise, starting in Paris\n| image_alt          = Map of France with the route of the 1907 Tour de France on it, showing that the race started in Paris, went clockwise through France and ended in Paris after fourteen stages.\n| image_size         = 300px\n| date               = 8 July \u2013 4 August\n| stages             = 14\n| distance           = 4488\n| unit               = km\n| time               = 47 points\n| first              = [[Lucien Petit-Breton]]\n| first_nat          = FRA\n| second             = [[Gustave Garrigou]]\n| second_nat         = FRA\n| third              = [[\u00c9mile Georget]]\n| third_nat          = FRA\n| previous           = [[1906 Tour de France|1906]]\n| next               = [[1908 Tour de France|1908]]\n}}\nThe '''1907 Tour de France''' was the fifth running of the annual [[Tour de France]], one of cycling's [[Grand Tour (cycling)|Grand Tours]]. From 8 July to 4 August, the 93 cyclists cycled 4488&nbsp;km (2,788&nbsp;mi) in fourteen stages around France. The winner, [[Lucien Petit-Breton]], completed the race at an average speed of 28.47&nbsp;km/h (17.69&nbsp;mi/h).<ref name=\"ASO\">{{cite web |url=http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/us/TDF/1906/histoire.html |title=1907 Tour de France |publisher=[[Amaury Sport Organisation]] |accessdate=2 April 2009 |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20090504023724/http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/TDF/1907/us/annee.html?RaceYear=1907&x=23&y=4 |archivedate=4 May 2009 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> For the first time, climbs in the Western Alps were included in the Tour de France. The race was dominated at the start by [[\u00c9mile Georget]], who won five of the first eight stages. In the ninth stage, he borrowed a bicycle from a befriended rider after his own broke. This was against the rules; initially he received only a small penalty and his main competitors left the race out of protest. Georget's penalty was then increased and [[Lucien Petit-Breton]] became the new leader. Petit-Breton won two of the remaining stages and the overall victory of the Tour.\n\n==Innovations==\nThe 1907 Tour de France incorporated 14 stages, which was one more than in 1906. For the first time, roads in Switzerland were included.<ref name=\"ASO\"/><ref name=\"mdc1907\"/> The mountain stages in 1906 had been so successful, according to the organiser [[Henri Desgrange]], that the western Alps were included in the race for the first time.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=19\u201322}}\n\nThe 1907 race was also the first time that a car with bicycle repairmen drove behind the riders, to give assistance in solving mechanical problems on bicycles.<ref name=\"mdc1907\"/>\n\nAs in 1906, the race was decided by a points system. At the end of every stage, the winner was given one point, the next cyclist two points, and so on. After the eighth stage, when there were only 49 cyclists left in the race, the points given in the first eight stages were redistributed among the remaining cyclists, according to their positions in those stages.<ref name=\"mdc1907\"/>\n\n==Participants==\n{{main list|List of cyclists in the 1907 Tour de France}}\n\n[[Ren\u00e9 Pottier]], the winner of the [[1906 Tour de France]], did not defend his title because he had committed suicide in early 1907.<ref name=\"mdc1907\"/> Although the riders officially rode the Tour as individuals, some shared the same sponsor and cooperated as if they rode in teams.{{sfn|Thompson|2006|p=36}} At the start of the race, it was expected that the riders sponsored by [[Alcyon]] and the riders sponsored by [[Peugeot]] would compete for the overall victory. Alcyon started with three main contenders: [[Louis Trousselier]], [[Marcel Cadolle]] and [[L\u00e9on Georget]]; Peugeot counted on [[Emile Georget]].{{sfn|Amels|1984|p=}}\n\nAs in the previous years, there were two classes of cyclists, the ''coureurs de vitesse'' and the ''coureurs sur machines poin\u00e7onn\u00e9es''. Of the 93 cyclists starting the race, 82 were in the ''poin\u00e7onn\u00e9e'' category, which meant that they had to finish the race on the same bicycle as they left, and if it was broken they had to fix it without assistance.{{sfn|Wheatcroft|2007|p=}} The ''coureurs de vitesse'' could get help from the car with bicycle repairmen when they had to fix a bicycle, and when a bicycle was beyond repair, they could change it to a new one.{{sfn|Laget|Montgermont|Cazaban|Laget|2013|p=}}\n\nNot all cyclists were competing for the victory; some only joined as tourists. The most notable of them was [[Henri P\u00e9pin]]. P\u00e9pin had hired two riders, [[Jean Dargassies]] and [[Henri Gauban]], to ride with him. They treated the race as a pleasure ride, stopping for lunch when they chose and spending the night in the best hotels they could find.{{sfn|Chany|Cazeneuve|1985|p=}} Dargassies and Gaubin became the first cyclists in the history of the Tour de France to ride not for their own placings but for another rider's interest. During the race, they found another Tour de France competitor, [[Jean-Marie Teychenne]], lying in a ditch. They helped him get up and fed him; from then on Teychenne also helped P\u00e9pin.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=19\u201322}}{{sfn|Dauncey|Hare|2003|p=73}}\n\n==Race overview==\n\n{{main|1907 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 7|1907 Tour de France, Stage 8 to Stage 14}}\n\nEarly in the race, Trousselier, [[Fran\u00e7ois Faber]] and Emile Georget were the main contenders.<ref name=\"ASO\"/> Trousselier, winner of the [[1905 Tour de France]] and eager to win again, won the first stage.{{sfn|Amels|1984|p=}} In the second stage, the Tour passed the French-German border to finish in Metz, which was then part of Germany. The German authorities allowed the cyclists to finish there, but did not allow the French flag to be flown or the cars of race officials to enter the city.{{sfn|Thompson|2006|p=68}} At the end of the stage, Emile Georget seemingly beat Trousselier with a very small margin. After inquiry, Desgrange, the Tour's organiser, decided to put both cyclists in first place,{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=9}} to keep both sponsors satisfied.{{sfn|Amels|1984|p=}}\n\nIn the third stage, the Tour returned to France; at the border, the riders were stopped by two French customs officers and the delay took so long that the stage had to be restarted.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=19\u201322}} During the stage in the Alps, \u00c9mile Georget was better than his competitors; he won the stage and became leader of the general classification.{{sfn|Amels|1984|p=}} Georget won five of the first eight stages, and had a commanding lead.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=19\u201322}} In the seventh stage, [[Marcel Cadolle]], at that time in second place,<ref>{{cite web|title=5\u00e8me Tour de France 1907 \u2013 6\u00e8me \u00e9tape |url=http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1907_6.php |publisher=M\u00e9moire du cyclisme |language=French |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090503114635/http://www.memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1907_6.php |archivedate=3 May 2009 |url-status=dead |accessdate=2 April 2009 }}</ref> fell and his handlebar penetrated his knee, after which he had to give up.{{sfn|Amels|1984|p=}}\n\n[[File:Lucien Mazan.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Lucien Petit-Breton]], the winner of the 1907 Tour de France|alt=A man on a bicycle, riding on an outdoor velodrome.]]During the ninth stage, when Georget was leading the race, he broke the frame of his bicycle{{sfn|Amels|1984|p=}} at a checkpoint. According to the rules, Georget should have fixed his bicycle alone; he knew this would take him more than five hours, so he switched bicycles with [[Pierre-Gonzague Privat]].{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=19\u201322}} This was against the rules, so Georget was given a fine of 500 francs.<ref name=\"ASO\"/><ref name=\"lpp28071907\">{{cite news|url=http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k5625856.zoom.f5.langFR|title=Le Tour de France|date=28 July 1907|accessdate=11 August 2010|page=5|work=Le Petit Parisien|language=French|publisher=Gallica Biblioth\u00e8que Num\u00e9rique}}</ref> After this stage, won by Petit-Breton, the general classification was as follows:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:20em\"\n|+General classification after stage 9<ref>{{cite news|url=http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k562583f.zoom.f4.langFR|title=Le Tour de France|date=26 July 1907|accessdate=11 August 2010|page=4|work=Le Petit Parisien|language=French|publisher=Gallica Biblioth\u00e8que Num\u00e9rique}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Rank !! scope=\"col\" | Rider !! scope=\"col\" | Points\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |1\n| \u00c9mile Georget || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 17\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |2\n| Lucien Petit-Breton || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 37\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |3\n| Louis Trousselier || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 40\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |4\n| Gustave Garrigou || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 53\n|}\n\nUnsatisfied with the fine given to Georget, Trousselier and the other riders sponsored by Alcyon left the Tour in protest.{{sfn|Amels|1984|p=}}<ref>{{cite news|url=http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k562584t.zoom.f4.langFR|title=Le Tour de France|date=27 July 1907|accessdate=11 August 2010|page=4|work=Le Petit Parisien|language=French|publisher=Gallica Biblioth\u00e8que Num\u00e9rique}}</ref>\n\nAfter the tenth stage, the organisers gave Georget an additional penalty for the bicycle change in the ninth stage. They changed the classification of the ninth stage, moving Georget from 4th on the stage to last (48th place).<ref name=\"lpp28071907\" /> This effectively cost him 44 points in the general classification and moved him from first to third place.<ref name=\"mdc1907s9\">{{cite web|url=http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1907_9.php|title=5\u00e8me Tour de France 1907 \u2013 9\u00e8me \u00e9tappe|language=French|accessdate=2 April 2009|publisher=M\u00e9moire du cyclisme| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090503114047/http://www.memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1907_9.php| archivedate= 3 May 2009 | url-status= dead}}</ref> The new classification, after the tenth stage, was\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:20em\"\n|+General classification after stage 10<ref name=\"lpp28071907\" />\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Rank !! scope=\"col\" | Rider !! scope=\"col\" | Points\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 1\n| Lucien Petit-Breton || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 39\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2\n| Gustave Garrigou || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 54\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 3\n| Emile Georget || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 64\n|}\n\n[[Lucien Petit-Breton]] became the new leader of the race. Although he had already finished in fifth place and fourth place in previous years,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/us/TDF/coureur/1362.html|publisher=[[Amaury Sport Organisation]]|title=Past results for Lucien MAZAN dit PETIT-BRETON (FRA)|accessdate=2 April 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304220153/http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/us/TDF/coureur/1362.html|archive-date=4 March 2016|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> he was still relatively unknown, and had started in the ''coureurs sur machines poin\u00e7onn\u00e9es'' category.<ref name=\"ASO\"/> Petit-Breton finished in the top three in the next stages, so no other cyclist was able to challenge him for the overall victory. At the end of the race, he had increased his lead to a margin of 19 points ahead of Garrigou and 27 points ahead of Georget.<ref name=\"mdc1907\"/>\n\n==Results==\n\n===Stage results===\n\nIn the first and final stages, the cyclists were allowed to have pacers.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k562565h.zoom.f5.langFR|title=Le Tour de France|language=French|work=[[Le Petit Parisien]]|pages=3\u20134|publisher=Gallica Biblioth\u00e9que Num\u00e8rique|date=8 July 1907|accessdate=11 August 2010}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Stage characteristics and winners<ref name=\"mdc1907\">{{cite web|url=http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1907.php|publisher=M\u00e9moire du cyclisme|title=5\u00e8me Tour de France 1907|language=French|accessdate=2 April 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090502202022/http://www.memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1907.php| archivedate= 2 May 2009| url-status= dead}}</ref>{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=9}}\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Stage\n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n! scope=\"col\" | Course\n! scope=\"col\" | Distance\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"2\" | Type{{efn|In 1907, there was no distinction in the rules between plain stages and mountain stages; the icons shown here indicate which stages included mountains.<ref name=\"mdc1907\"/>}}\n! scope=\"col\" | Winner\n! scope=\"col\" | Race leader\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1907 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 7#Stage 1|1]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 8 July || [[Paris]] to [[Roubaix]]\n| {{convert|272|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Louis Trousselier]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Louis Trousselier]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1907 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 7#Stage 2|2]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 10 July || [[Roubaix]] to [[Metz]]\n| {{convert|398|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Emile Georget]]|FRA}}{{efn|name=shared|At first, Georget was declared winner, but after investigation by tour organiser [[Henri Desgrange]], Trousselier was also declared winner.{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=9}}}}<br/>{{flagathlete|[[Louis Trousselier]]|FRA}}{{efn|name=shared}} || {{flagathlete|[[Louis Trousselier]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1907 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 7#Stage 3|3]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 12 July || [[Metz]] to [[Belfort]]\n| {{convert|259|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s)|| {{flagathlete|[[Emile Georget]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Emile Georget]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1907 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 7#Stage 4|4]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 14 July || [[Belfort]] to [[Lyon]]\n| {{convert|309|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s)|| {{flagathlete|[[Marcel Cadolle]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Emile Georget]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1907 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 7#Stage 5|5]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 16 July || [[Lyon]] to [[Grenoble]]\n| {{convert|311|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s)|| {{flagathlete|[[Emile Georget]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Emile Georget]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1907 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 7#Stage 6|6]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 18 July || [[Grenoble]] to [[Nice]]\n| {{convert|345|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s)|| {{flagathlete|[[Georges Passerieu]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Emile Georget]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1907 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 7#Stage 7|7]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 20 July || [[Nice]] to [[N\u00eemes]]\n| {{convert|345|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Emile Georget]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Emile Georget]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1907 Tour de France, Stage 8 to Stage 14#Stage 8|8]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 22 July || [[N\u00eemes]] to [[Toulouse]]\n| {{convert|303|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Emile Georget]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Emile Georget]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1907 Tour de France, Stage 8 to Stage 14#Stage 9|9]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 24 July || [[Toulouse]] to [[Bayonne]]\n| {{convert|299|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Lucien Petit-Breton]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Emile Georget]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1907 Tour de France, Stage 8 to Stage 14#Stage 10|10]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 26 July || [[Bayonne]] to [[Bordeaux]]\n| {{convert|269|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Gustave Garrigou]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Lucien Petit-Breton]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1907 Tour de France, Stage 8 to Stage 14#Stage 11|11]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 28 July || [[Bordeaux]] to [[Nantes]]\n| {{convert|391|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Lucien Petit-Breton]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Lucien Petit-Breton]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1907 Tour de France, Stage 8 to Stage 14#Stage 12|12]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 30 July || [[Nantes]] to [[Brest, France|Brest]]\n| {{convert|321|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Gustave Garrigou]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Lucien Petit-Breton]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1907 Tour de France, Stage 8 to Stage 14#Stage 13|13]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 1 August || [[Brest, France|Brest]] to [[Caen]]\n| {{convert|415|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Emile Georget]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Lucien Petit-Breton]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1907 Tour de France, Stage 8 to Stage 14#Stage 14|14]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 4 August || [[Caen]] to [[Paris]]\n| {{convert|251|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Georges Passerieu]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Lucien Petit-Breton]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\"| Total\n| colspan=\"5\" style=\"text-align:center\"| {{convert|4488|km|0|abbr=on}}{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=108}}\n|}\n\n===General classification===\n\nAlthough 110 riders were on the starting list, 17 did not show up, so the race started with 93 cyclists. At the end of the Tour de France, 33 cyclists remained.<ref name=\"mdc1907\" />\nThe cyclists officially were not grouped in teams; some cyclists had the same sponsor, even though they were not allowed to work together.{{sfn|Thompson|2006|p=36}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:44em; margin-bottom:0;\"\n|+ Final general classification (1\u201310)<ref name=\"mdc1907\"/><ref name=\"elm\">{{cite web|url=http://hemeroteca-paginas.mundodeportivo.com/EMD02/HEM/1907/08/08/MD19070808-006.pdf|title=Le Tour de France|date=8 August 1907|page=6|language=Spanish|work=[[Mundo Deportivo]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191006131100/http://hemeroteca-paginas.mundodeportivo.com/EMD02/HEM/1907/08/08/MD19070808-006.pdf|archive-date=6 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Rank!! scope=\"col\" | Rider!! scope=\"col\" | Sponsor!! scope=\"col\" | Points!! scope=\"col\" | Category\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 1\n| {{flagathlete|[[Lucien Petit-Breton]]|FRA}} || [[Peugeot (cycling team)|Peugeot-Wolber]] || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 47 || Poin\u00e7onn\u00e9es\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 2\n| {{flagathlete|[[Gustave Garrigou]]|FRA}} || [[Peugeot (cycling team)|Peugeot-Wolber]] || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 66 || Vitesse\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 3\n| {{flagathlete|[[Emile Georget]]|FRA}} || [[Peugeot (cycling team)|Peugeot-Wolber]] || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 74 || Vitesse\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 4\n| {{flagathlete|[[Georges Passerieu]]|FRA}} || [[Peugeot (cycling team)|Peugeot-Wolber]] || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 85 || Vitesse\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 5\n| {{flagathlete|[[Fran\u00e7ois Beaugendre]]|FRA}} || [[Peugeot (cycling team)|Peugeot-Wolber]] || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 123 || Poin\u00e7onn\u00e9es\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 6\n| {{flagathlete|[[Eberardo Pavesi]]|ITA|1861}} || Otav || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 150 || Poin\u00e7onn\u00e9es\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 7\n| {{flagathlete|[[Fran\u00e7ois Faber]]|LUX}} || Labor-Dunlop || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 156 || Poin\u00e7onn\u00e9es\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 8\n| {{flagathlete|[[Augustin Ringeval]]|FRA}} || Labor-Dunlop || align=right|184 || Vitesse\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 9\n| {{flagathlete|[[Alo\u00efs Catteau]]|BEL}} || \u2013 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 196 || Poin\u00e7onn\u00e9es\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 10\n| {{flagathlete|[[Ferdinand Payan]]|FRA}} || \u2013 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 227 || Poin\u00e7onn\u00e9es\n|}\n{| class=\"collapsible collapsed wikitable noprint\" style=\"width:44em; margin-top:-1px;\"\n|-\n!colspan=5|Final general classification (11\u201333)\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Rank!! scope=\"col\" | Rider!! scope=\"col\" | Sponsor!! scope=\"col\" | Points!! scope=\"col\" | Category\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 11\n| {{flagathlete|[[Pierre-Gonzague Privat]]|FRA}} || \u2013 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 251 || Vitesse\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 12\n| {{flagathlete|[[Georges Fleury]]|FRA}} || \u2013 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 274 || Poin\u00e7onn\u00e9es\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 13\n| {{flagathlete|[[Fran\u00e7ois Lafourcade]]|FRA}} || Montabro || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 299 || Poin\u00e7onn\u00e9es\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 14\n| {{flagathlete|[[Marius Villette]]|FRA}} || \u2013 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 333 || Poin\u00e7onn\u00e9es\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 15\n| {{flagathlete|[[Alzir Vivier]]|FRA}} || \u2013 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 340 || Poin\u00e7onn\u00e9es\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 16\n| {{flagathlete|[[Gaston Tuvache]]|FRA}} || \u2013 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 348 || Poin\u00e7onn\u00e9es\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 17\n| {{flagathlete|[[Eug\u00e8ne Delhaye]]|BEL}} || \u2013 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 378 || Poin\u00e7onn\u00e9es\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 18\n| {{flagathlete|[[Baptiste Roux]]|FRA}} || \u2013 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 389 || Vitesse\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 19\n| {{flagathlete|[[Philippe Pautrat]]|FRA}} || \u2013 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 393 || Vitesse\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 20\n| {{flagathlete|[[Henri Timmermann]]|BEL}} || \u2013 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 411 || Poin\u00e7onn\u00e9es\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 21\n| {{flagathlete|[[Georges Bronchard]]|FRA}} || \u2013 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 414 || Poin\u00e7onn\u00e9es\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 22\n| {{flagathlete|[[Marceau Narcy]]|FRA}} || Biguet-Soly || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 416 || Poin\u00e7onn\u00e9es\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 23\n| {{flagathlete|[[Honor\u00e9 Genin]]|FRA}} || [[Peugeot (cycling team)|Peugeot-Wolber]] || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 434 || Vitesse\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 24\n| {{flagathlete|[[Antony Wattelier]]|FRA}} || Labor-Dunlop/Montabro || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 436 || Vitesse\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 25\n| {{flagathlete|[[Albert Baudet]]|FRA}} || \u2013 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 439 || Poin\u00e7onn\u00e9es\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 26\n| {{flagathlete|[[Alfred Le Bars]]|FRA}} || Labor-Dunlop || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 479 || Vitesse\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 27\n| {{flagathlete|[[Alfred Quenon]]|FRA}} || \u2013 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 487 || Poin\u00e7onn\u00e9es\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 28\n| {{flagathlete|[[Henri Lorillon]]|FRA}} || Touiller || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 491 || Vitesse\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 29\n| {{flagathlete|[[Ren\u00e9 Fleury]]|FRA}} || \u2013 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 495 || Poin\u00e7onn\u00e9es\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 30\n| {{flagathlete|[[Octave No\u00ebl]]|FRA}} || Furor Cycles || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 505 || Poin\u00e7onn\u00e9es\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 31\n| {{flagathlete|[[Albert G\u00e9raud]]|FRA}} || JC Cycles || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 515 || Poin\u00e7onn\u00e9es\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 32\n| {{flagathlete|[[Marcel Dozol]]|FRA}} || \u2013 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 522 || Poin\u00e7onn\u00e9es\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 33\n| {{flagathlete|[[Albert Chartier (cyclist)|Albert Chartier]]|FRA}} || \u2013 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 568 || Poin\u00e7onn\u00e9es\n|}\n\nThe total prize money was 25000 [[French franc]]s, of which 4000 francs were given to Petit-Breton for winning the Tour.{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=9}} In total, he received more than 7000 francs.<ref name=\"elm\"/>\n\n===Other classifications===\nLucien Petit-Breton was also the winner of the \"machines poin\u00e7onn\u00e9es\" category.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/fr/TDF/1907/histoire.html|title=l'Historique du Tour \u2013 Ann\u00e9e 1907|language=French|publisher=[[Amaury Sport Organisation]]|accessdate=2 January 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100716170709/http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/fr/TDF/1907/histoire.html|archive-date=16 July 2010|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe organising newspaper l'Auto named [[Emile Georget]] the ''meilleur grimpeur''. This unofficial title is the precursor to the modern-day [[mountains classification in the Tour de France|mountains classification]].{{sfn|Cleijne|2014|p=156}}\n\n==Aftermath==\nPetit-Breton also started the [[1908 Tour de France]]. He won five stages and the general classification, and became the first cyclist to win the Tour de France two times.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.veloarchive.com/races/tour/1908.php|title=1908: Petit-Breton becomes the first double-winner|publisher=Veloarchive|author=James, Tom|date=27 August 2007|accessdate=16 August 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book|last=Amels|first=Wim|title=De geschiedenis van de Tour de France 1903\u20131984|location=Valkenswaard, Netherlands|publisher=Sport-Express|year=1984|language=Dutch|isbn=978-90-70763-05-3|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|first=Jacques|last=Augendre|author-link=Jacques Augendre|url=http://netstorage.lequipe.fr/ASO/cyclisme/le-tour/2016/histoire/TDF16_GH_Interactif-PROD.pdf|title=Guide historique|trans-title=Historical guide|year=2016|language=French|access-date=27 October 2016|format=PDF|work=[[Tour de France]]|location=Paris|publisher=[[Amaury Sport Organisation]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160817121602/http://netstorage.lequipe.fr/ASO/cyclisme/le-tour/2016/histoire/TDF16_GH_Interactif-PROD.pdf|archive-date=17 August 2016|url-status=live|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Chany|first1=Pierre|authorlink1=Pierre Chany|last2=Cazeneuve|first2=Thierry|title=La Fabuleuse Histoire du Tour de France|year=1985|location=France|publisher=ODIL|language=French|isbn=978-2-8307-0689-5|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Cleijne|first=Jan|title=Legends of the Tour|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3nCNAwAAQBAJ|year=2014|location=London|publisher=Head of Zeus|isbn=978-1-78185-998-8|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Dauncey|last2=Hare|first1=Hugh|first2=Geoff|title=The Tour de France, 1903\u20132003: A Century of Sporting Structures, Meanings and Values|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=54pAJY6Ix8YC|year=2003|publisher=[[Frank Cass & Co]]|location=London|isbn=978-0-203-50241-9|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Laget|first1=Fran\u00e7oise|last2=Montgermont|first2=Gilles|last3=Cazaban|first3=Philippe|last4=Laget|first4=Serge|title=Tour de France: The Official 100th Race Anniversary Edition|url=https://books.google.com/?id=pRFhBQAAQBAJ|year=2013|publisher=[[Hachette UK]]|location=London|isbn=978-1-78206-415-2|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=McGann|first1=Bill|last2=McGann|first2=Carol|title=The Story of the Tour de France: 1903\u20131964|volume=1|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jxq20JskqMUC|publisher=Dog Ear Publishing|location=Indianapolis, IN|year=2006|isbn=978-1-59858-180-5|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Thompson|first=Christopher S.|title=The Tour de France: A Cultural History|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=M-vUF6Y_4RUC|publisher=[[University of California Press]]|location=Oakland, CA|year=2006|isbn=978-0-520-24760-4|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Wheatcroft|first=Geoffrey|url=https://archive.org/details/letourhistoryoft0000whea|url-access=registration|title=Le Tour: A History of the Tour De France|location=New York City|publisher=[[Simon & Schuster]]|year=2007|isbn=978-1-84739-086-8|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category-inline|Tour de France 1907|1907 Tour de France}}\n\n{{Cycling stage recaps|1907 Tour de France|1|7|8|14}}\n{{Tour de France}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1907 Tour de France}}\n[[Category:1907 Tour de France| ]]\n[[Category:1907 in French sport|Tour de France]]\n[[Category:Tour de France by year]]\n[[Category:1907 in road cycling|Tour de France]]\n[[Category:July 1907 sports events|Tour de France]]\n[[Category:August 1907 sports events|Tour de France]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2019}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Infobox cycling race report\n| name               = 1907 Tour de France\n| image              = Tour de France 1907 map-fr.svg\n| image_caption      = Route of the 1907 Tour de France followed clockwise, starting in Paris\n| image_alt          = Map of France with the route of the 1907 Tour de France on it, showing that the race started in Paris, went clockwise through France and ended in Paris after fourteen stages.\n| image_size         = 300px\n| date               = 8 July \u2013 4 August\n| stages             = 14\n| distance           = 4488\n| unit               = km\n| time               = 47 points\n| first              = [[Lucien Petit-Breton]]\n| first_nat          = FRA\n| second             = [[Gustave Garrigou]]\n| second_nat         = FRA\n| third              = [[\u00c9mile Georget]]\n| third_nat          = FRA\n| previous           = [[1906 Tour de France|1906]]\n| next               = [[1908 Tour de France|1908]]\n}}\nThe '''1907 Tour de France''' was the fifth running of the annual [[Tour de France]], one of cycling's [[Grand Tour (cycling)|Grand Tours]]. From 8 July to 4 August, the 93 cyclists cycled 4488&nbsp;km (2,788&nbsp;mi) in fourteen stages around France. The winner, [[Lucien Petit-Breton]], completed the race at an average speed of 28.47&nbsp;km/h (17.69&nbsp;mi/h).<ref name=\"ASO\">{{cite web |url=http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/us/TDF/1906/histoire.html |title=1907 Tour de France |publisher=[[Amaury Sport Organisation]] |accessdate=2 April 2009 |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20090504023724/http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/TDF/1907/us/annee.html?RaceYear=1907&x=23&y=4 |archivedate=4 May 2009 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> For the first time, climbs in the Western Alps were included in the Tour de France. The race was dominated at the start by [[\u00c9mile Georget]], who won five of the first eight stages. In the ninth stage, he borrowed a bicycle from a befriended rider after his own broke. This was against the rules; initially he received only a small penalty and his main competitors left the race out of protest. Georget's penalty was then increased and [[Lucien Petit-Breton]] became the new leader. Petit-Breton won two of the remaining stages and the overall victory of the Tour.\n\n==Changes from the previous Tour==\nThe 1907 Tour de France incorporated 14 stages, which was one more than in 1906. For the first time, roads in Switzerland were included.<ref name=\"ASO\"/><ref name=\"mdc1907\"/> The mountain stages in 1906 had been so successful, according to the organiser [[Henri Desgrange]], that the western Alps were included in the race for the first time.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=19\u201322}}\n\nThe 1907 race was also the first time that a car with bicycle repairmen drove behind the riders, to give assistance in solving mechanical problems on bicycles.<ref name=\"mdc1907\"/>\n\nAs in 1906, the race was decided by a points system. At the end of every stage, the winner was given one point, the next cyclist two points, and so on. After the eighth stage, when there were only 49 cyclists left in the race, the points given in the first eight stages were redistributed among the remaining cyclists, according to their positions in those stages.<ref name=\"mdc1907\"/>\n\n==Participants==\n{{main list|List of cyclists in the 1907 Tour de France}}\n\n[[Ren\u00e9 Pottier]], the winner of the [[1906 Tour de France]], did not defend his title because he had committed suicide in early 1907.<ref name=\"mdc1907\"/> Although the riders officially rode the Tour as individuals, some shared the same sponsor and cooperated as if they rode in teams.{{sfn|Thompson|2006|p=36}} At the start of the race, it was expected that the riders sponsored by [[Alcyon]] and the riders sponsored by [[Peugeot]] would compete for the overall victory. Alcyon started with three main contenders: [[Louis Trousselier]], [[Marcel Cadolle]] and [[L\u00e9on Georget]]; Peugeot counted on [[Emile Georget]].{{sfn|Amels|1984|p=}}\n\nAs in the previous years, there were two classes of cyclists, the ''coureurs de vitesse'' and the ''coureurs sur machines poin\u00e7onn\u00e9es''. Of the 93 cyclists starting the race, 82 were in the ''poin\u00e7onn\u00e9e'' category, which meant that they had to finish the race on the same bicycle as they left, and if it was broken they had to fix it without assistance.{{sfn|Wheatcroft|2007|p=}} The ''coureurs de vitesse'' could get help from the car with bicycle repairmen when they had to fix a bicycle, and when a bicycle was beyond repair, they could change it to a new one.{{sfn|Laget|Montgermont|Cazaban|Laget|2013|p=}}\n\nNot all cyclists were competing for the victory; some only joined as tourists. The most notable of them was [[Henri P\u00e9pin]]. P\u00e9pin had hired two riders, [[Jean Dargassies]] and [[Henri Gauban]], to ride with him. They treated the race as a pleasure ride, stopping for lunch when they chose and spending the night in the best hotels they could find.{{sfn|Chany|Cazeneuve|1985|p=}} Dargassies and Gaubin became the first cyclists in the history of the Tour de France to ride not for their own placings but for another rider's interest. During the race, they found another Tour de France competitor, [[Jean-Marie Teychenne]], lying in a ditch. They helped him get up and fed him; from then on Teychenne also helped P\u00e9pin.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=19\u201322}}{{sfn|Dauncey|Hare|2003|p=73}}\n\n==Race overview==\n\n{{main|1907 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 7|1907 Tour de France, Stage 8 to Stage 14}}\n\nEarly in the race, Trousselier, [[Fran\u00e7ois Faber]] and Emile Georget were the main contenders.<ref name=\"ASO\"/> Trousselier, winner of the [[1905 Tour de France]] and eager to win again, won the first stage.{{sfn|Amels|1984|p=}} In the second stage, the Tour passed the French-German border to finish in Metz, which was then part of Germany. The German authorities allowed the cyclists to finish there, but did not allow the French flag to be flown or the cars of race officials to enter the city.{{sfn|Thompson|2006|p=68}} At the end of the stage, Emile Georget seemingly beat Trousselier with a very small margin. After inquiry, Desgrange, the Tour's organiser, decided to put both cyclists in first place,{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=9}} to keep both sponsors satisfied.{{sfn|Amels|1984|p=}}\n\nIn the third stage, the Tour returned to France; at the border, the riders were stopped by two French customs officers and the delay took so long that the stage had to be restarted.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=19\u201322}} During the stage in the Alps, \u00c9mile Georget was better than his competitors; he won the stage and became leader of the general classification.{{sfn|Amels|1984|p=}} Georget won five of the first eight stages, and had a commanding lead.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=19\u201322}} In the seventh stage, [[Marcel Cadolle]], at that time in second place,<ref>{{cite web|title=5\u00e8me Tour de France 1907 \u2013 6\u00e8me \u00e9tape |url=http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1907_6.php |publisher=M\u00e9moire du cyclisme |language=French |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090503114635/http://www.memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1907_6.php |archivedate=3 May 2009 |url-status=dead |accessdate=2 April 2009 }}</ref> fell and his handlebar penetrated his knee, after which he had to give up.{{sfn|Amels|1984|p=}}\n\n[[File:Lucien Mazan.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Lucien Petit-Breton]], the winner of the 1907 Tour de France|alt=A man on a bicycle, riding on an outdoor velodrome.]]During the ninth stage, when Georget was leading the race, he broke the frame of his bicycle{{sfn|Amels|1984|p=}} at a checkpoint. According to the rules, Georget should have fixed his bicycle alone; he knew this would take him more than five hours, so he switched bicycles with [[Pierre-Gonzague Privat]].{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=19\u201322}} This was against the rules, so Georget was given a fine of 500 francs.<ref name=\"ASO\"/><ref name=\"lpp28071907\">{{cite news|url=http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k5625856.zoom.f5.langFR|title=Le Tour de France|date=28 July 1907|accessdate=11 August 2010|page=5|work=Le Petit Parisien|language=French|publisher=Gallica Biblioth\u00e8que Num\u00e9rique}}</ref> After this stage, won by Petit-Breton, the general classification was as follows:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:20em\"\n|+General classification after stage 9<ref>{{cite news|url=http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k562583f.zoom.f4.langFR|title=Le Tour de France|date=26 July 1907|accessdate=11 August 2010|page=4|work=Le Petit Parisien|language=French|publisher=Gallica Biblioth\u00e8que Num\u00e9rique}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Rank !! scope=\"col\" | Rider !! scope=\"col\" | Points\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |1\n| \u00c9mile Georget || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 17\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |2\n| Lucien Petit-Breton || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 37\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |3\n| Louis Trousselier || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 40\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |4\n| Gustave Garrigou || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 53\n|}\n\nUnsatisfied with the fine given to Georget, Trousselier and the other riders sponsored by Alcyon left the Tour in protest.{{sfn|Amels|1984|p=}}<ref>{{cite news|url=http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k562584t.zoom.f4.langFR|title=Le Tour de France|date=27 July 1907|accessdate=11 August 2010|page=4|work=Le Petit Parisien|language=French|publisher=Gallica Biblioth\u00e8que Num\u00e9rique}}</ref>\n\nAfter the tenth stage, the organisers gave Georget an additional penalty for the bicycle change in the ninth stage. They changed the classification of the ninth stage, moving Georget from 4th on the stage to last (48th place).<ref name=\"lpp28071907\" /> This effectively cost him 44 points in the general classification and moved him from first to third place.<ref name=\"mdc1907s9\">{{cite web|url=http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1907_9.php|title=5\u00e8me Tour de France 1907 \u2013 9\u00e8me \u00e9tappe|language=French|accessdate=2 April 2009|publisher=M\u00e9moire du cyclisme| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090503114047/http://www.memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1907_9.php| archivedate= 3 May 2009 | url-status= dead}}</ref> The new classification, after the tenth stage, was\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:20em\"\n|+General classification after stage 10<ref name=\"lpp28071907\" />\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Rank !! scope=\"col\" | Rider !! scope=\"col\" | Points\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 1\n| Lucien Petit-Breton || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 39\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2\n| Gustave Garrigou || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 54\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 3\n| Emile Georget || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 64\n|}\n\n[[Lucien Petit-Breton]] became the new leader of the race. Although he had already finished in fifth place and fourth place in previous years,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/us/TDF/coureur/1362.html|publisher=[[Amaury Sport Organisation]]|title=Past results for Lucien MAZAN dit PETIT-BRETON (FRA)|accessdate=2 April 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304220153/http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/us/TDF/coureur/1362.html|archive-date=4 March 2016|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> he was still relatively unknown, and had started in the ''coureurs sur machines poin\u00e7onn\u00e9es'' category.<ref name=\"ASO\"/> Petit-Breton finished in the top three in the next stages, so no other cyclist was able to challenge him for the overall victory. At the end of the race, he had increased his lead to a margin of 19 points ahead of Garrigou and 27 points ahead of Georget.<ref name=\"mdc1907\"/>\n\n==Results==\n\n===Stage results===\n\nIn the first and final stages, the cyclists were allowed to have pacers.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k562565h.zoom.f5.langFR|title=Le Tour de France|language=French|work=[[Le Petit Parisien]]|pages=3\u20134|publisher=Gallica Biblioth\u00e9que Num\u00e8rique|date=8 July 1907|accessdate=11 August 2010}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Stage characteristics and winners<ref name=\"mdc1907\">{{cite web|url=http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1907.php|publisher=M\u00e9moire du cyclisme|title=5\u00e8me Tour de France 1907|language=French|accessdate=2 April 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090502202022/http://www.memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1907.php| archivedate= 2 May 2009| url-status= dead}}</ref>{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=9}}\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Stage\n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n! scope=\"col\" | Course\n! scope=\"col\" | Distance\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"2\" | Type{{efn|In 1907, there was no distinction in the rules between plain stages and mountain stages; the icons shown here indicate which stages included mountains.<ref name=\"mdc1907\"/>}}\n! scope=\"col\" | Winner\n! scope=\"col\" | Race leader\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1907 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 7#Stage 1|1]]\n| 